          "body": "When deception fails, David commits what the Law calls premeditated murder: he writes a letter to Joab commanding that Uriah be placed at the front of the fiercest battle and then abandoned, 'so that he may be struck down and die' (11:15). The detail that Uriah himself carries the letter is the chapter's most grotesque irony — the condemned man is trusted to deliver his own death warrant, a trust that is itself a monument to Uriah's integrity and David's depravity. Peter Davids, writing on the New Testament's theology of temptation, notes that desire conceived is already sin regardless of whether the act follows (James 1:15); here the act has followed, and it is murder. The murder is deniable because it is embedded in battle — 'some of the people among David's servants fell; and Uriah the Hittite also died' (11:17). War provides the cover that domestic deception could not. Joab, who knows perfectly well what the order means, places Uriah where he will die."
