        "excerpt": "At the time when kings go out to battle… But David stayed at Jerusalem.",
        "body": "The single verse that opens the chapter carries more theological freight than any battle report in the books of Samuel. The narrator's phrase 'at the time when kings go out to battle' (*le-teshuvat ha-shanah*, literally 'at the return of the year,' the annual campaign season) is not merely a calendar note — it is a covenantal norm statement. Israel's king was not an administrative monarch who delegated military affairs; he was the shepherd-warrior whose personal leadership of the army was his primary calling (1 Samuel 8:20; 2 Samuel 5:2). David had exemplified this in every campaign recorded in chapters 5–10: he went, he fought, he returned. The first words of chapter 11 establish that pattern — and then the 'but' arrives.\n\nThe theological significance of David's staying has been underweighted in popular readings that focus immediately on the adultery. But the opening dereliction is not merely context — it is causation. Idleness, luxury, and the removal of the disciplines that shaped David as a shepherd-boy and fugitive have softened him into a man who rises at evening rather than at dawn (11:2). Chuck Swindoll identifies this as the 'danger of the rooftop' — the moment when a leader whose character was forged in hardship finds himself in a position where the hardship has been removed and the structures of accountability with it. David at war is accountable to his men, to the mission, to the risk of death. David on the roof is accountable to no one in the room.\n\nWithin the canonical structure of 2 Samuel, chapter 11:1 is the hinge between the two halves of the book. Chapters 1–10 constitute the ascent: David consolidates the kingdom, brings the ark to Jerusalem, receives the Davidic covenant in chapter 7, defeats every surrounding nation. Chapter 11 is the turning point; chapters 12–24 are the long descent. The seeds of every subsequent catastrophe — Nathan's curse of the sword in David's house (12:10-12), Amnon's rape of Tamar (13:1-14), Absalom's rebellion (15-18), the census and plague (24) — are planted in the 'but' of 11:1.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yashav* (stayed, dwelt, sat) — the same verb used of kings seated on thrones; the irony is that David is 'seated' when he should be standing at the front. *Teshuvah ha-shanah* (the return/turning of the year) — campaign season is named a 'turning,' which the narrator turns into a moral turning-point."
