        "excerpt": "From the roof he saw a woman bathing; and the woman was very beautiful in appearance.",
        "body": "The sequence from 11:2 to 11:5 is the Old Testament's most detailed anatomy of the passage from temptation to sin, and it maps precisely onto the chain James 1:14-15 will later articulate: desire (*epithumia*) → conception → sin → death. Here the chain is: see (11:2) → inquire (11:3) → send and take (11:4) → conceive (11:5). Each step is an act of will, not an irresistible force. The narrator omits internal deliberation; what we see is action — and that omission is the point. David does not appear to wrestle. He sees, and sends.\n\nThe identification of Bathsheba as 'the wife of Uriah the Hittite' (11:3) is the chapter's moral fulcrum. The question the unnamed servant asks David — 'Is this not Bathsheba, the daughter of Eliam, the wife of Uriah the Hittite?' — reads like a gentle warning. Bathsheba's father Eliam was one of David's thirty mighty men (2 Samuel 23:34), meaning David almost certainly knew the family personally. Uriah the Hittite himself appears on the same list of thirty (2 Samuel 23:39) — he was among Israel's most elite soldiers, a man whose name ('my light is Yahweh') indicates either personal faith or a family thoroughly assimilated into Yahwistic worship. The servant's identification is an implicit 'do you know what you are doing?' David sends anyway.\n\nThe legal precision of verse 4b — 'she had purified herself from her uncleanness' — is the narrator's evidentiary signature. Leviticus 15:19-28 prescribed a purification period after menstruation, after which the woman was ritually clean and marital relations were permitted. The notation establishes that Bathsheba was at the point in her cycle where conception was possible, and that her purification had been completed away from Uriah (who was at the front). There is no ambiguity about paternity. The narrator has anticipated the defence before it can be offered.\n\nJonathan Edwards, in his sermon 'Warnings against Spiritual Sloth,' notes that the believer's greatest vulnerability is not in the moments of extreme trial but in the moments of unstructured ease, when no external pressure is pressing the soul toward God. David at war prays (2 Samuel 5:19, 23); David on the roof does not."
