        "excerpt": "The ark and Israel and Judah are staying in temporary shelters… Shall I then go to my house to eat and to drink and to lie with my wife?",
        "body": "The cover-up section (11:6-13) is the chapter's most theologically rich movement, and its hero is a Hittite. Uriah appears eight times by name in this section alone, each occurrence tightening the contrast between the man David is trying to manipulate and the man David has ceased to be. Three times David attempts to send Uriah home — with a direct order (11:8), with an extended stay (11:12), and with alcohol (11:13). Three times Uriah refuses. The refusals are not merely stubborn; they are theologically articulate.\n\nUriah's speech in 11:11 is the chapter's most important utterance. He names three entities that prevent him from going home: 'the ark,' 'Israel,' and 'Judah.' The ark is the covenant symbol of Yahweh's presence with the army (cf. 1 Samuel 4:3-11, where its capture was national catastrophe). Israel and Judah together name the full covenant people. Uriah understands himself as embedded in a web of covenantal obligations from which personal comfort cannot excuse him. His oath — 'By your life and the life of your soul, I will not do this thing' — invokes the king's own life as the standard he is meeting. The irony is comprehensive: Uriah is appealing to the integrity of a man who has none left, and the standard he sets by the king's name the king himself is violating.\n\nCommentators in the Reformed tradition (Calvin, *Commentaries on Samuel*, 1561) have noted that the Hittite label attached to Uriah every time he is named is not ethnic slur but theological pointer. Israel was commanded not to intermarry with Canaanite peoples (Deuteronomy 7:3-4), yet here a man from that stock outperforms the covenant heir. The pattern has precedent: Rahab the harlot, Ruth the Moabite, the Gibeonite deception that resulted in covenant-keeping David later honouring (2 Samuel 21:1-14). God is not confined to covenant Israel for examples of covenant faithfulness. The foreigner's integrity indicts the insider's apostasy.\n\nThe drunken dinner (11:13) is the final indignity David offers Uriah before turning to murder. Intoxication is deployed as a tool to lower Uriah's resistance — to make him go home without the full exercise of his theological convictions. It fails. 'He did not go down to his house' (11:13). The three 'buts' of this section (11:9, 11, 13) constitute the chapter's counter-narrative: every time David pushes, Uriah holds. The cover-up has reached its terminus.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Sukkah* (temporary shelters, booths) — the same word used for the Feast of Tabernacles shelters, evoking Israel's wilderness sojourn; Uriah's language places the current army experience within the larger narrative of Israel's dependence on Yahweh."
