        "body": "The letter David writes in 11:14-15 is one of Scripture's most carefully narrated acts of premeditated murder. The narrator slows the scene to ensure nothing is missed: 'David wrote a letter to Joab and sent it by the hand of Uriah' — then, as if the reader needs a moment, 'He had written in the letter, saying…' What follows is not a vague instruction but a specific tactical order with a specific intended outcome: place Uriah at the front, withdraw, let him die. There is no plausible deniability. This is *wilful* killing of a *named* man whose specific position the letter designates.\n\nThe detail that Uriah carries his own death warrant — a detail the narrator does not pass over but highlights — is the chapter's most morally intense image. It is not unique in ancient literature (the Greek myth of Bellerophon, sent to Lycia with a sealed letter requesting his death, comes from roughly the same period), but its presence here functions theologically. Uriah's faithfulness in carrying out David's orders, even to his own death, is one final measurement of the character gap between them. He trusts his king with the sealed message; his king has sealed his fate.\n\nJoab's execution of the order is technically competent (11:16) — he places Uriah 'at the place where he knew there were valiant men,' so the death looks like an outcome of bold tactics near a fortified wall rather than an assassination. The battle report in 11:17 buries Uriah's name in a list of casualties: 'some of the people among David's servants fell; and Uriah the Hittite also died.' The 'also' is the bureaucratic disguise — Uriah is one name among others. But the narrator's subsequent refusal to release Uriah's name (repeating it in 11:21, 24) ensures the disguise fails in the reader's hands.\n\nWithin the canonical theology of the Mosaic covenant, David has now broken the Sixth Commandment (murder, Exodus 20:13), the Seventh (adultery, Exodus 20:14), the Tenth (coveting a neighbour's wife, Exodus 20:17), and arguably the Ninth (false witness, by constructing a false narrative around Uriah's death). The king entrusted with the covenant is its most comprehensive violator. Douglas Moo, reflecting on the New Testament's use of Old Testament law, argues that covenantal sin at the leadership level carries amplified consequences precisely because the leader's role is representative; Nathan's oracle in chapter 12 will confirm that the punishment falls not only on David but on his house."
